          <td bgcolor="" valign="top" width="1"><img src="/magination/gfx/trans_header1.gif" width="22" height="2" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td>
          <td bgcolor="" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
  <tr>
    <td>
      <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
        <tr>
          <td>
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
              <tr> 
                <td class="chpurple"><font class="h1font"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3"><tr><td><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Elios Tactics<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=9064'>Danny "Woven" Young</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=9064&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 16, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont">  First of all, here&#39;s Elios:<br>
<br>
Elios<br>
Arderial Magi<br>
10<br>
Starting: None (?)<br>
Energize: 8 (!)<br>
Effect-Dream Hard: At the beggining of your energize step, choose a number less than Elios&#39;s energize rate. Decrease his energize by that much and draw that many cards during your draw step instead of the normal two.<br>
Effect- When Elios is defeated, discard all but 5 cards from your hand. <br>
<br>
 Wow... here we have a magi that has the ability to alter his energize and draw steps to suit whatever he needs more of... energy and things to waste that energy on!<br>
 The problem Elios has is the unnamed effect that tells you to practically through your hard-earned hand away. For this, we atomatically think that we should put him in our last magi slot. Bad idea! Here&#39;s why: First of all, he won&#39;t get any new cards when he comes in to play. Second of all, Elios is one of those odd magi that for some reason can&#39;t stay alive for long when you put them in the wrong slot. Have you ever noticed magi like that? As soon as you give them a new slot, they start working much better and staying alive much longer. So lets give Elios our number one slot.<br>
 There are two things we can do to counteract the unnammed effect(we&#39;ll just call it... Unnamed). First is to find out what you don&#39;t need for your next magi. Let&#39;s say you have a hand of 15. Throw away the next magi&#39;s starting cards, you&#39;ll get them back right away. This gives you 12. Then throw away your next magi&#39;s starting card for the same reason. 9. You now have 4 extra cards. Look at what just killed Elios. Throw away everything that won&#39;t help your next magi stop that, and keep a few utility cards and some cards that go good with your next mage. The second way to counteract Unnamed is.... win the whole game with Elios!<br>
 Ok, that can be tough to do with any magi, and Elios is no exception. So how do we give him the time he needs to burn through your entire deck and bunches of energy? It&#39;s all in how well you manipulate Dream Hard. <br>
 Let&#39;s say you go first. This gives you only ten energy, but it also gives you 5 random cards to start with. Now look at your hand. Play a creature or two that will leave energy on Elios and give him protection. If you have a Vellup, get them all. Got a Xyx or two? Go ahead. Got a Grand Epik? No!!! Avoid giving Elios a Grand Epik at all costs. It leaves him with a 6 energize with which to manipulate Dream Hard, and that is not enough. You could, however play an Orathan Flyer and use his energy to bring out another creature. Got a Rayalon? Good choice. But you get the picture by now. Give him enough to stay alive. If you have a Tranquiity, play it for protection against sneak attacks and to get another card at turn&#39;s end.<br>
 If you go second, it&#39;s time to let the fun start! Look at your opponent&#39;s side. Do you have a sufficient hand to bring them down or to defend against them? If you do, call a low number such as 1, 2, or 3. This gives Elios anywhere from an above-average energize rate with low drawing(1), slightly above-average energize with normal drawing(2), or average energize with above-average drawing(3). If you don&#39;t have sufficient means of defense, call 4. This gives you 14 energy to work with and 4 cards at the end of your turn. <br>
 Always leave Elios enough energy to use effectively. If your opponent is about to steamroll you, give him some energy to play a defensive hand and some options on the next turn. Got a Cataclysm? How much energy do you currently have? Give him enough energy to play the Cataclysm and have enough to survive a sneak attack, and give him at least one card at the end of your turn. If you have a way to get around card drawing, do it! Elios goes great with Cloud Sceptre. Does your opponent have a Secrets of the Book? They&#39;ve just doomed themselves to face an eight energize magi with a slew of cards... if you have Sorreah&#39;s Dream. And if you&#39;re playing Arderial, you have Sorreah&#39;s Dream, right? Or you can work your way around the energy portion of the effect. Let&#39;s see what happens. You play Staff of Keepers and three Tree Hinko (6). Use Invigorate and as many Sorreah&#39;s Dreams as you can and then drop a Water of Life. On your next turn, you energize for, say, with two Dreams, 19 energy. Call out a nice number like 9 or 10. You&#39;ll energize for 10 or 9 and get 9 or 10 cards at turn&#39;s end. And you&#39;ve still got another round of Hinkos! When you have a good hand, leave yourself with a bunch of energy and at least one card to draw. Even if you can&#39;t get around part of Dream Hard, you can still manage. If you need energy, give him energy! If you need wisdom, give him some cards! If you have a big hand, you could even call out 0 to give him 8 energy. Four, five, and six are great numbers for Elios to work with. <br>
 And now, go have some fun with Elios. After a few games of practice, knowing what numbers to call will be second nature to you... and your opponent will be left on the ground as Elios soars over them! <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/magination/articles/articles.php?id=3312&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/magination/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></td></tr></table></td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </td>
